rifolium'')\n*[[Rosa chinensis|China rose]]}} -->| website                         = [https://web.archive.org/web/20160115003057/http://www.xm.gov.cn/ www.xm.gov.cn]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese| showflag = poj | order = st\n| l = \"Mansion Gate\"<ref>Formerly \"Lower Gate\" ({{lang|zh-hant|\u4e0b\u9580}}); see Name section.</ref>\n| pic = Xiamen_(Chinese_characters).svg\n| piccap = \"Xiamen\" in Simplified (top) and Traditional (bottom) Chinese characters\n| picupright = 0.45\n| s = \u53a6\u95e8 | t = \u5ec8\u9580\n| p = Xi\u00e0m\u00e9n | w = Hsia<sup>4</sup>-m\u00ean<sup>2</sup> | mi = {{IPAc-cmn|AUD|Xiamen pronunciation.ogg|x|ia|4|.|m|en|2}}\n| psp = Amoy\n| poj = \u0112-mn\u0302g ''or'' \u0112-m\u00fbi\n| buc = \u00c2-mu\u00f2ng\n| j = Haa<sup>6</sup>-mun<sup>4</sup> | y = Haah-m\u00f9hn | ci = {{IPAc-yue|h|aa|6|.|m|un|4}}\n| suz = Gh\u00f4-m\u00e9n\n| gan = Ha<sup>5</sup>-mun<sup>4</sup>\n| h = H\u00e0-m\u00fbn\n| altname = \n}}\n{{stack end}}\n\n'''Xiamen''' (Chinese:\u53a6\u95e8 {{IPAc-en|UK|\u0283|(|j|)|\u0251\u02d0|\u02c8|m|\u025b|n}} {{respell|sh(y)ah|MEN}}, {{IPAc-en|US|-|\u02c8|m|V|n}} {{respell|-|MUN}}), [[Postal Map romanization|alternately]] known as '''Amoy''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0259|\u02c8|m|\u0254\u026a}},<ref>{{OED|Amoy}}</ref> from [[Hokkien]] pronunciation {{IPA-taiwan|e\u02e8\u02e9 m\u014b\u030d\u02e8|}}), is a [[sub-provincial city]] in southeastern [[Fujian]], People's Republic of China, beside the [[Taiwan Strait]]. It is divided into six [[District of the People's Republic of China|districts]]: [[Huli District|Huli]], [[Siming District|Siming]], [[Jimei District|Jimei]], [[Tong'an]], [[Haicang District|Haicang]], and [[Xiang'an]]. All together, these cover an area of {{convert|1699.39|km2|sp=us}} with a population of 3,531,347 as of [[2010 Chinese census|2010]]. The [[urbanization in China|urbanized]] area of the city has spread from its original island to include parts of all six of its [[District of the People's Republic of China|districts]], with a total population of 1,861,289. This area connects to [[Quanzhou]] in the north and [[Zhangzhou]] in the west, making up a metropolis of more than five million people. The [[Kinmen]] Islands (Quemoy) administered by the [[Republic of China]] lie less than {{convert|6|km|sp=us|0}} away.\n\n[[Xiamen Island]] possessed a natural harbor in Yundang Bay, but Fujian's international trade was [[Sea Ban|long restricted]] to [[Quanzhou]] or to [[Guangzhou]] in Guangdong. Due to the [[siltification]] of Quanzhou's harbor, the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] insisted that Xiamen be [[treaty ports|opened to foreign trade]] in the [[Treaty of Nanking|treaty]] that ended the [[First Opium War]] in 1842. Under the [[Qing dynasty|Qing]], both before and after the war, there was a large-scale [[Chinese diaspora|emigration of Chinese]] from southern Fujian who spread [[Hokkien]]-speaking communities to Singapore, [[Malaysia]] (especially in [[Penang]]), [[Indonesia]] ([[Medan]] and [[Riau Province]]) and the [[Philippines]]. The [[overseas Chinese]] continue to support Xiamen's educational and cultural institutions. As part of the [[Opening Up Policy]] under [[Deng Xiaoping]], Xiamen became one of China's original four [[Special Economic Zones of the People's Republic of China|special economic zones]] opened to foreign investment and trade in the early 1980s. Its former harbor [[land reclamation|was enclosed]] using land excavated during the city's expansion, however, the city remains an island connected by bridges to the rest of mainland China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hot Terms in China's Reform |url=http://english.cri.cn/3126/2008/10/31/53s419804.htm |accessdate=17 August 2018 |publisher=CRI English |date=31 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817124848/http://english.cri.cn/3126/2008/10/31/53s419804.htm |archive-date=17 August 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe city is well known for its mild climate, Hokkien culture and [[Gulangyu Island]], as well as its relatively low pollution. In 2006, Xiamen was ranked as China's second-\"most suitable city for living\", as well as China's \"most romantic leisure city\" in 2011. \n{{TOClimit|3}}\n{{anchor|Etymology|Names}}\n\n==Name==\n[[File:Zheng Chenggong.JPG|thumb|left|200px|The statue of [[Koxinga]] (Zheng Chenggong) on [[Gulangyu Island]].]]\nThe area around [[Xiamen Bay]] appears as '''Tong'an''' in some [[Han dynasty|Han]] records. [[Xiamen Island]] was described as '''Jiahe Islet''' during the Song Dynasty (960\u20131279). It received its present name from the Xiamen Castle erected on the island by [[Zhou Dexing]] in 1387 during the [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] to meet the needs of coastal defense.<ref name=zgddc>''Zhongguo Gujin Diming Da Cidian'' \u4e2d\u56fd\u53e4\u4eca\u5730\u540d\u5927\u8bcd\u5178, 2855.</ref> The name was formerly written using the [[Chinese characters]] meaning \"Lower Gate\" and then changed into \"\u53a6\u95e8\", meaning \"Mansion Gate\" or \"Gate of China\".\n\nBy the end of Ming Dynasty, [[Koxinga|Zheng Chenggong]], or Koxinga, a Ming loyalist, occupied Xiamen as an anti-[[Qing dynasty|Qing]] base. In 1650, the seventh year of Emperor Shunzhi of the Qing Dynasty, Zheng set a military base in Xiamen and changed its name into \"\u601d\u660e\u5dde\", or \"Siming\", meaning \"Remembering the Ming\".\n\nWhen its port prospered under the [[Qing dynasty|Qing]], especially during the reign of Emperor Kangxi, the name was changed to \"\u53a6\u95e8\", or \"Xiamen\", again.\n\nThe name of Siming was in return restored after the [[Xinhai Revolution]] that inaugurated the [[Republic of China (mainland)|republic]] in 1912.\n\nThe name of Xiamen was restored in 1933, along with Xiamen being administratively planned as a city, the first of its kind in Fujian province. Siming continues to be used as the name of one of its districts.\n\nXiamen is the [[Chinese tones|atonal]] [[pinyin]] [[romanization of Chinese|romanization]] of the characters' pronunciation in [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin]]. It has also been romanized as '''Hiamen'''.<!--not a typo-->{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} The former English name \"Amoy\" was based on the same name's pronunciation in the [[Zhangzhou dialect]] of [[Hokkien language|Hokkien]], ''\u0112-m\u00fbi''.\n\n==Geography==\n{{main|Xiamen Island|Xiamen Bay}}\n[[File:Aerial photography Xiamen Island.JPG|left|thumb|200px|[[Xiamen Island]], looking south. The [[Gaoji Causeway]] lies at the bottom and the old Yundang Harbor\u2014now an inclosed lake\u2014lies to the right. The [[Kinmen]] Islands (Quemoy), [[Republic of China]] (Taiwan) can be seen in the upper half of the photograph. The photo was taken aboard a [[China Eastern Airlines|China Eastern]] [[Airbus A320-214]].]]\nXiamen is a [[sub-provincial city]] in southeastern [[Fujian]] whose urban core grew up from the port of Xiamen on southern [[Xiamen Island]], now located within [[Siming District]]. It now also includes [[Gulangyu Island]] and the rugged coast of the mainland from the northeast bank of the [[Jiulong River]] in the west to the islands of [[Xiang'an]] in the east. Xiamen Island lies about one degree north of the [[Tropic of Cancer]].<ref name=cancer>{{harvp|Pitcher|1893|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=K8QIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26 26]}}.</ref> It is divided between [[Huli District]] in the north and [[Siming District]] in the south. Siming also includes Gulangyu. Its mainland territory is divided among [[Haicang District|Haicang]], [[Jimei District|Jimei]], [[Tong'an District|Tong'an]], and [[Xiang'an District|Xiang'an]] districts.\n\nIn the 19th century, Xiamen's harbor on Yundang Bay was considered one of the world's great natural harbors. [[Land reclamation]] has since been used to fill in the mouth of this inlet, turning it into Siming District's Yundang Lake. The municipal government is located on other reclaimed land beside it.\n\nThe nearest point of [[Lieyu|Liehyu]] in the [[Kinmen]] Islands (Quemoy), [[Republic of China]] (Taiwan), lies only {{convert|6|km|sp=us|0}} off Xiamen Island.<ref>[http://www1.china.com.cn/chinese/ChineseCommunity/138060.htm \u300a\u73af\u7403\u65f6\u62a5\u300b2002-04-22] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325134702/http://www1.china.com.cn/chinese/ChineseCommunity/138060.htm |date=25 March 2012 }}. .china.com.cn. Retrieved 28 August 2011.</ref>\n\nXiamen Island is the fourth largest island in Fujian province. It became a peninsula after the completion of the seawall in 1955. Xiamen waters include Xiamen Port, Outer Harbor Area, Maluan Bay, Tongan Bay, Jiulong River's estuary area and the waterway on the east side. Outside the Xiamen Port, Big Kinmen, Little Kinmen, Dadan, Erdan and other island are arranged in a horizontal line. Inside, it has Xiamen Island, Gulangyu Island and other island barriers, making it a good natural port protected from storms.\n\n===Climate===\nXiamen has a [[monsoon]]al [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Cfa''), characterised by long, hot and humid summers (but moderate compared to much of the rest of the province) and short, mild and dry winters. The warmest month is July, with a 24-hour average of {{convert|27.8|\u00b0C|sp=us|1}}, and the coolest month is January, averaging {{convert|12.8|\u00b0C|sp=us|1}}; the annual mean is {{convert|20.7|\u00b0C|sp=us|1}}. Extremes since 1951 have ranged from {{convert|1.5|\u00b0C|sp=us|0}} on 29 December 1991 to {{convert|39.2|\u00b0C|sp=us|0}} on 20 July 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdc.cma.gov.cn/dataSetLogger.do?changeFlag%3DdataLogger |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318113757/http://cdc.cma.gov.cn/dataSetLogger.do?changeFlag=dataLogger |archivedate=18 March 2013 }}</ref> Spring, both by humidity and percentage of sunshine, is the dampest season but typhoons in late summer and early autumn can make the latter period wetter overall. Summer and autumn are marked by comparatively sunny conditions, while autumn is warm and dry. The annual rainfall is {{convert|1350|mm|sp=us|0}}. With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 24% in March to 56% in July, the city receives 1,853 hours of bright sunshine annually. Frost occurs very rarely, and the last snowfall in the city took place in January 1893, when snow also fell at [[Guangzhou]], Macau, in the inland parts of Hong Kong and in the hills of [[Taipei]].\n\nThe area is known within China for its relatively low pollution.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/chinas-10-least-polluted-cities-map-2013-2 |title=These 10 Cities Are Your Best Bet at Escaping China's Epic Pollution Problem |first=Rob |last=Wile |accessdate=17 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816144612/http://www.businessinsider.com/chinas-10-least-polluted-cities-map-2013-2 |archive-date=16 August 2016 |url-status=live  }}.</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|metric first=y\n|single line=y\n|collapsed = Y\n|location = Xiamen (1981\u20132010)\n|Jan high C = 17.3\n|Feb high C = 17.5\n|Mar high C = 19.5\n|Apr high C = 23.5\n|May high C = 27.0\n|Jun high C = 29.7\n|Jul high C = 32.2\n|Aug high C = 32.0\n|Sep high C = 30.4\n|Oct high C = 27.5\n|Nov high C = 23.8\n|Dec high C = 19.4\n|Jan mean C = 12.8\n|Feb mean C = 13.1\n|Mar mean C = 15.0\n|Apr mean C = 19.1\n|May mean C = 22.9\n|Jun mean C = 26.0\n|Jul mean C = 28.0\n|Aug mean C = 27.8\n|Sep mean C = 26.3\n|Oct mean C = 23.2\n|Nov mean C = 19.3\n|Dec mean C = 14.9\n|year mean C =\n|Jan low C = 10.0\n|Feb low C = 10.4\n|Mar low C = 12.1\n|Apr low C = 16.2\n|May low C = 20.3\n|Jun low C = 23.5\n|Jul low C = 25.2\n|Aug low C = 25.1\n|Sep low C = 23.6\n|Oct low C = 20.5\n|Nov low C = 16.5\n|Dec low C = 12.0\n|Jan record high C = 28.4 |Jan record low C = 2.0\n|Feb record high C = 28.4 |Feb record low C = 2.6\n|Mar record high C = 29.6 |Mar record low C = 2.5\n