{"title_page": "Guido Carocci", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian historian}}\n{{Expand Italian|Guido Carocci|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Guido Carocci.jpg|thumb|Carocci]]\n'''Guido Carocci''' (16 September 1851 - 20 September 1916) was an Italian historian of [[Florence]] and its historic buildings. He was born and died in the city. He was also director of its [[National Museum of San Marco]] and fought the destruction of the city centre by the building works of the ''Risanamento''. He is buried in the [[Cimitero di Soffiano]].\n\n==Sources==\n* G. Carocci, [http://www.bollettinodarte.beniculturali.it/opencms/multimedia/BollettinoArteIt/documents/1347285088896_2-_Guido_Carocci_p._1.pdf ''Gli affreschi di Andrea del Castagno nella villa Pandolfini presso Firenze''], Bollettino d'Arte, 8, 1907\n* G. Carocci, [http://www.bollettinodarte.beniculturali.it/opencms/multimedia/BollettinoArteIt/documents/1344607225596_04_-_Guido_Carocci_p._379.pdf ''Il Museo di S. Marco di Firenze ed alcuni suoi nuovi acquisti''], Bollettino d'Arte, 10, 1911\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carocci, Guido}}\n[[Category:Italian architectural historians]]\n[[Category:Directors of museums in Italy]]\n[[Category:1851 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Florence]]\n[[Category:History of Florence]]\n\n\n{{Italy-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian historian}}\n{{Expand Italian|Guido Carocci|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Guido Carocci.jpg|thumb|Carocci]]\n'''Guido Carocci''' (16 September 1851 - 20 September 1916) was an Italian historian of [[Florence]] and its historic buildings. He was born and died in the city. He was also director of its [[National Museum of San Marco]] and fought the destruction of the city centre by the building works of the ''Risanamento''. He is buried in the [[Cimitero di Soffiano]].\n\n==Sources==\n* G. Carocci, [http://www.bollettinodarte.beniculturali.it/opencms/multimedia/BollettinoArteIt/documents/1347285088896_2-_Guido_Carocci_p._1.pdf ''Gli affreschi di Andrea del Castagno nella villa Pandolfini presso Firenze''], Bollettino d'Arte, 8, 1907\n* G. Carocci, [http://www.bollettinodarte.beniculturali.it/opencms/multimedia/BollettinoArteIt/documents/1344607225596_04_-_Guido_Carocci_p._379.pdf ''Il Museo di S. Marco di Firenze ed alcuni suoi nuovi acquisti''], Bollettino d'Arte, 10, 1911\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carocci, Guido}}\n{{Italy-historian-stub}}\n[[category:Italian architectural historians]]\n[[Category:Directors of museums in Italy]]\n[[category:1851 births]]\n[[category:1916 deaths]]\n[[category:People from Florence]]\n[[category:History of Florence]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guido_Carocci"}
{"title_page": "2016 Super League Grand Final", "text_new": "{{Infobox rugby league football match\n|year         = 2016\n|title        = Super League Grand Final\n|image        = \n|imagesize    = \n|alt          = \n|home         = [[Warrington Wolves]]\n|away         = [[Wigan Warriors]]\n|home_abbr    = WAR {{leagueicon|Warrington|16}}\n|away_abbr    = WIG {{leagueicon|Wigan|16}}\n|home_half1   = 6\n|home_half2   = 0\n|home_total   = 6\n|away_half1   = 2\n|away_half2   = 10\n|away_total   = 12\n|date         = 8 October 2016\n|stadium      = [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]]\n|location     =  {{flagicon|ENG}} Manchester\n|MoM_title    = [[Harry Sunderland Trophy]]\n|MoM          = {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Liam Farrell]] ({{leagueicon|wigan|16}} [[Wigan Warriors]])\n|anthem_title = Headliners\n|anthem       = [[Feeder (band)|Feeder]]\n|referee      = Robert Hicks\n|attendance   = 70,202\n|network      = [[Sky Sports]]\n|commentators = [[Eddie Hemmings (rugby league)|Eddie Hemmings]]\n|commentators2= \n|commentators3= \n|tournaments  = [[Super League Grand Final]]\n|last         = [[2015 Super League Grand Final|2015]]\n|next         = [[2017 Super League Grand Final|2017]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2016 Super League Grand Final''' was the conclusive and championship-deciding match of the [[Super League XXI]] season. It was held on Saturday 8 October 2016,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rugby-league.com/article/33212/tickets|title=2016 FIRST UTILITY SUPER LEAGUE FIXTURES ANNOUNCED|date=18 October 2015|work=RUGBY-LEAGUE.COM|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]], Manchester, with a 6pm kick-off time. British rock band [[Feeder (band)|Feeder]] provided the pre-match and half-time entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rugby-league.com/article/38256/feeder-to-headline-entertainment-at-grand-final|title=FEEDER TO HEADLINE ENTERTAINMENT AT GRAND FINAL|date=15 August 2016|work=RUGBY-LEAGUE.COM|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> The [[Wigan Warriors]] were crowned champions, winning their fourth Super League crown, and prevented [[Warrington Wolves|Warrington]] from winning their first championship in 61 years.\n\n==Background==\n{{further|Super League XXI}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Position\"| Pos\n! style=\"width:175px;\"| Team\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Played\"| Pld\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Won\"| W\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Drawn\"| D\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Lost\"| L\n! style=\"width:25px;\" abbr=\"Points for\"| PF\n! style=\"width:25px;\" abbr=\"Points against\"| PA\n! style=\"width:25px;\" abbr=\"Points difference\"| PD\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Points\"| Pts\n|- \n| 1 ||style=\"text-align:left\"| {{leagueicon|Warrington|16}} [[Warrington Wolves]]\n| 30 || 21 || 1 || 8 || 944 || 650 || +311 || '''43'''\n|- \n| 2 ||style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{leagueicon|Wigan|16}} [[Wigan Warriors]]\n| 30 || 21 || 0 || 9 || 669 || 560 || +109 || '''42'''\n|}\n\n===Route to the Final===\n====Warrington Wolves====\n{{See|2016 Warrington Wolves season}}\nWarrington's back end of the season started badly when they lost at the Challenge cup final, when they lost 12-10 against [[Hull F.C.|Hull FC]]. Then in the rematch of the final, Warrington won 23-6 to win the League. They then beat [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] for only the 2nd time at the [[Halliwell Jones Stadium]] to clinch the first Final spot.\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;margin-left:1em;float:right\"\n<!-- |+ '''Leeds''' -->\n!width=\"25\" | Round\n!width=\"150\" | Opposition\n!width=\"60\" | Score\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"| Semi-Final\n| {{leagueicon|st helens|16}} [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]] (H)\n|bgcolor=DDFFDD| 18-10\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:white;\"| <small>'''Key:''' (H) = Home venue; (A) = Away venue; (N) = [[Home advantage#Neutral venues|Neutral venue]].</small>\n|}\n\n===Wigan Warriors===\n{{See|2016 Wigan Warriors season}}\nWigan have been quieter than usual this season, however in the back end of the season Wigan have fought back to finish second by beating [[Hull F.C.]] and [[Warrington Wolves]] away. However, they have lost their last 2 grand finals, and beat the wolves in 2013. \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;margin-left:1em;float:right\"\n<!-- |+ '''Leeds''' -->\n!width=\"25\" | Round\n!width=\"150\" | Opposition\n!width=\"60\" | Score\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"| Semi-Final\n| {{leagueicon|hull|16}} [[Hull F.C.]] (H)\n|bgcolor=DDFFDD| 28-18\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:white;\"| <small>'''Key:''' (H) = Home venue; (A) = Away venue; (N) = [[Home advantage#Neutral venues|Neutral venue]].</small>\n|}\n\n==Match day==\n===Pre-game===\nThe match was a rematch of the [[2013 Super League Grand Final]], where Wigan won the trophy after trailing at half-time. This is Wigan's fourth consecutive Grand Final appearance. Warrington have been in the Grand Final twice before and have never won the Super League trophy, with their last league trophy win coming 61 years ago in the [[1954\u201355 Northern Rugby Football League season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/37545067|title=Grand Final: Warrington and Wigan set for Super League's 2016 final|date=7 October 2016|work=BBC SPORT RUGBY LEAGUE|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nWigan were underdogs coming into this match as a host of their regular players were missing through injury. Players such as [[Sam Tomkins|Sam]] and [[Joel Tomkins]], [[Michael McIlorum]], [[Dominic Manfredi]], and [[Lee Mossop]]. Skipper [[Sean O'Loughlin]] was also amongst this list but was rushed into the team for the Grand Final and was placed on the bench after two 'successful' training sessions. Warrington's [[Chris Sandow]] was also a late inclusion for the Grand Final after he recovered enough to play, however he also started the game on the reserves bench.\n\nThis was the last rugby league match for Wigan's [[Josh Charnley]] before heading off to play rugby union. Teammate, [[Lewis Tierney]], son of [[1998 Super League Grand Final]] winner and dual-international, [[Jason Robinson (rugby player)|Jason Robinson]], created history by becoming the first son to play in a Grand Final after his father did.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/rugby-league/550000/Lewis-Tierney-Grand-Final-Saturday-Rugby-League-Wigan-Warriors|title=Lewis Tierney will write his name in the Grand Final history books on Saturday|date=1 October 2016|work=DAILY STAR|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> Notably, Oliver Gildart's father [[Ian Gildart]] had also won various silverware with Wigan, but this was prior to the Super League era.\n\n==Match details==\n{{rugbyleaguebox\n|bg = C1D8FF\n|date = 8 October 2016<br />18:00 [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n|team1 = [[Warrington Wolves]] {{leagueicon|Warrington|16}}\n|score = 6 \u2013 12 \n|report = ([https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/37550948 Report])\n|team2 = {{leagueicon|Wigan|16}} [[Wigan Warriors]]\n|points1 = '''Tries:''' [[Declan Patton|Patton]] {{try|21}}<br>'''Goals:''' [[Declan Patton|Patton]] (1/1) 22'\n|points2 = '''Tries:''' [[Oliver Gildart|Gildart]] {{try|55}}<br>[[Josh Charnley|Charnley]] {{try|63}}<br>'''Goals:''' [[Matty Smith|Smith]] (2/4) 8', 74'\n|stadium = [[Old Trafford]], [[Manchester]] \n|attendance = 70,202\n|referee = Robert Hicks\n|manofmatch = [[Liam Farrell]]\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:138px; background:blue; color:yellow; border:2px solid yellow;\"|'''Warrington Wolves'''\n![[Rugby league positions|Position]]\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:138px; background:red; color:white; border:2px solid white;\"|'''Wigan Warriors'''\n|-\n!6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Stefan Ratchford]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|FB}}\n!4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Dan Sarginson]]\n|-\n!2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Tom Lineham]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Rlp|WG}}\n!2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Josh Charnley]]\n|-\n!3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Rhys Evans (rugby league)|Rhys Evans]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{Rlp|CE}}\n!3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Anthony Gelling]]\n|-\n!4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ryan Atkins]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|CE}}\n!20\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Oliver Gildart]]\n|-\n!5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Matty Russell]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|WG}}\n!22\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Lewis Tierney]]\n|-\n!1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Kurt Gidley]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|SO}}\n!6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[George Williams (rugby league)|George Williams]]\n|-\n!26\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Declan Patton]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|SH}}\n!7\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Matty Smith]]\n|-\n!10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ashton Sims]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|PR}}\n!24\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Frank-Paul Nu'uausala]] \n|-\n!9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Daryl Clark]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|HK}}\n!16\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sam Powell]]\n|-\n!8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Chris Hill (rugby league)|Chris Hill]] ([[Captain (sports)|c]]) \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|PR}}\n!10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ben Flower]] \n|-\n!12\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Jack Hughes (rugby league)|Jack Hughes]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|SR}}\n!12\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Liam Farrell]]\n|-\n!27\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sam Wilde]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|SR}}\n!14\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[John Bateman (rugby league)|John Bateman]]\n|-\n!14\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Joe Westerman]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{rlp|LF}}\n!25\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Willie Isa]] \n|-\n| style=background:black; colspan=5 | \n|-\n!7\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Chris Sandow]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Interchange\n!8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Dom Crosby]]\n|-\n!18\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[George King (rugby league)|George King]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Interchange\n!13\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sean O'Loughlin]]  ([[Captain (sports)|c]])\n|-\n!24\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Toby King]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Interchange\n!19\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Taulima Tautai]] \n|-\n!33\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ryan Bailey (rugby league)|Ryan Bailey]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Interchange\n!21\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ryan Sutton]]\n|-\n| style=background:black; colspan=5 | \n|-\n!\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Tony Smith (rugby league born 1967)|Tony Smith]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Coach\n!\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Shaun Wane]]\n|}\n\n===First Half===\nWigan opened the scoring in the 8th minute with a penalty goal from [[Matty Smith]] due to teammate, [[John Bateman (rugby league)|John Bateman]], being held too long in a tackle.\n\nIn the 17th minute, Wigan dotted the ball on the line out wide with [[Josh Charnley|Charnley]], however the try wasn't awarded, due to a flick from [[Anthony Gelling|Gelling]] which went forward due to pressure from Warrington's defence. This was Wigan's only notable effort in the first half as errors, such as this one, from both teams cost them opportunities.\n\nHowever, in the 21st minute, Warrington did score, thanks to a try from [[Declan Patton]], who was only making his 9th appearance of the season. He then converted his own try to give his team a 6\u20132 lead, which they'd hold onto until half-time.<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/rugby-league/super-league-grand-final-wigan-warriors-vs-warrington-wolves-match-report-josh-charnley-a7352246.html|title=Super League Grand Final: Josh Charnley signs off in style as Wigan Warriors defeat Warrington Wolves|date=8 October 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Second Half===\nIn the 54th minute, [[Ryan Atkins]] made his way over the try-line for Warrington. However, referee Robert Hicks sent the final decision to [[Television Match Official|Video Referee]] [[Ben Thaler]], as he couldn't see whether or not the ball was grounded on the try-line, after 5 Wigan players were tackling Atkins. Eventually after a short delay, Hicks' initial TRY decision was overturned by video referee, Ben Thaler, due to Atkins seen losing control of the ball before he could get it down.<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rugby-league/2016/10/08/josh-charnley-signs-off-with-wigan-winner-in-super-league-grand|title=Josh Charnley signs off with Wigan winner in Super League Grand Final|date=8 October 2016|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nA minute later, [[Liam Farrell]] broke Warrington's defensive line, and then gave a pass off to [[Oliver Gildart]], who'd go on to score the 100th Super League Grand Final try. After kicking from a wide angle, [[Matty Smith]] was unable to convert and the scores remained level.\n\nIn the 63rd minute, [[Josh Charnley]] wasn't denied this time around, scoring after grounding the departing team member [[Dan Sarginson]]'s grubber in the in-goal area. Matty Smith again had to convert from out wide, but he again failed to capitalise on the extra 2 points.\n\nSmith then finally added another two points, courtesy of a penalty goal, conceded by [[Daryl Clark]]. The penalty-goal made the score 12\u20136 to Wigan with only 6 minutes remaining. After this moment, all the chances belonged to Warrington, but Wigan's defence stood up when it mattered most, tackling players out of play and tackling them on the 5th tackle, to create a turnover each time. Wigan held on to win their 4th Super League title.<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2016/oct/08/super-league-grand-final-warrington-wigan-live|title=Warrington 6-12 Wigan: Super League Grand Final \u2013 as it happened!|date=8 October 2016|work=Guardian|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-match===\nWigan's victory was their fourth Super League title.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/oct/08/warrington-wigan-super-league-grand-final-match-report|title=Wigan\u2019s Josh Charnley downs Warrington in Super League Grand Final|date=8 October 2016|work=theguardian|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nLiam Farrell won the [[Harry Sunderland Trophy]]/ Man of the Match award \n\nThe match was also the last for SkySports commentator, and former Great Britain international, [[Mike Stephenson|Stevo]], after 26 years of commentating the sport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/12198/10607868/farewell-to-stevo-sky-sports-pundits-pay-tribute-to-mike-stephenson|title=Farewell to Stevo: Sky Sports pundits pay tribute to Mike Stephenson|date=7 October 2016|work=skySPORTS|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==World Club Series==\n{{main|2017 World Club Series}}\nBy winning this match Wigan had qualified for the [[World Club Challenge|World Club Series]] Final, to be played at [[DW Stadium]] against the winners of the [[2016 NRL Grand Final]], the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]]. Warrington, as the runners up, would play 2016 NRL Grand Final runners up [[Melbourne Storm]] at the [[Halliwell Jones Stadium]]. The third game would have seen Challenge Cup champions [[Hull F.C.]] take on [[Canberra Raiders]] at [[KCOM Stadium]]. However circumstances later dictated that only Wigan and Warrington would play games, against Cronulla and Brisbane Broncos respectively.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Super League}}\n{{2016 in rugby league}}\n\n[[Category:Warrington Wolves matches]]\n[[Category:Wigan Warriors matches]]\n[[Category:Super League Grand Finals]]\n[[Category:Super League XXI|Grand Final]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rugby league football match\n|year         = 2016\n|title        = Super League Grand Final\n|image        = \n|imagesize    = \n|alt          = \n|home         = [[Warrington Wolves]]\n|away         = [[Wigan Warriors]]\n|home_abbr    = WAR {{leagueicon|Warrington|16}}\n|away_abbr    = WIG {{leagueicon|Wigan|16}}\n|home_half1   = 6\n|home_half2   = 0\n|home_total   = 6\n|away_half1   = 2\n|away_half2   = 10\n|away_total   = 12\n|date         = 8 October 2016\n|stadium      = [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]]\n|location     =  {{flagicon|ENG}} Manchester\n|MoM_title    = [[Harry Sunderland Trophy]]\n|MoM          = {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Liam Farrell]] ({{leagueicon|wigan|16}} [[Wigan Warriors]])\n|anthem_title = Headliners\n|anthem       = [[Feeder]]\n|referee      = Robert Hicks\n|attendance   = 70,202\n|network      = [[Sky Sports]]\n|commentators = [[Eddie Hemmings (rugby league)|Eddie Hemmings]]\n|commentators2= \n|commentators3= \n|tournaments  = [[Super League Grand Final]]\n|last         = [[2015 Super League Grand Final|2015]]\n|next         = [[2017 Super League Grand Final|2017]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2016 Super League Grand Final''' was the conclusive and championship-deciding match of the [[Super League XXI]] season. It was held on Saturday 8 October 2016,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rugby-league.com/article/33212/tickets|title=2016 FIRST UTILITY SUPER LEAGUE FIXTURES ANNOUNCED|date=18 October 2015|work=RUGBY-LEAGUE.COM|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]], Manchester, with a 6pm kick-off time. British rock band [[Feeder (band)|Feeder]] provided the pre-match and half-time entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rugby-league.com/article/38256/feeder-to-headline-entertainment-at-grand-final|title=FEEDER TO HEADLINE ENTERTAINMENT AT GRAND FINAL|date=15 August 2016|work=RUGBY-LEAGUE.COM|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> The [[Wigan Warriors]] were crowned champions, winning their fourth Super League crown, and prevented [[Warrington Wolves|Warrington]] from winning their first championship in 61 years.\n\n==Background==\n{{further|Super League XXI}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Position\"| Pos\n! style=\"width:175px;\"| Team\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Played\"| Pld\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Won\"| W\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Drawn\"| D\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Lost\"| L\n! style=\"width:25px;\" abbr=\"Points for\"| PF\n! style=\"width:25px;\" abbr=\"Points against\"| PA\n! style=\"width:25px;\" abbr=\"Points difference\"| PD\n! style=\"width:20px;\" abbr=\"Points\"| Pts\n|- \n| 1 ||style=\"text-align:left\"| {{leagueicon|Warrington|16}} [[Warrington Wolves]]\n| 30 || 21 || 1 || 8 || 944 || 650 || +311 || '''43'''\n|- \n| 2 ||style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{leagueicon|Wigan|16}} [[Wigan Warriors]]\n| 30 || 21 || 0 || 9 || 669 || 560 || +109 || '''42'''\n|}\n\n===Route to the Final===\n====Warrington Wolves====\n{{See|2016 Warrington Wolves season}}\nWarrington's back end of the season started badly when they lost at the Challenge cup final, when they lost 12-10 against [[Hull F.C.|Hull FC]]. Then in the rematch of the final, Warrington won 23-6 to win the League. They then beat [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] for only the 2nd time at the [[Halliwell Jones Stadium]] to clinch the first Final spot.\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;margin-left:1em;float:right\"\n<!-- |+ '''Leeds''' -->\n!width=\"25\" | Round\n!width=\"150\" | Opposition\n!width=\"60\" | Score\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"| Semi-Final\n| {{leagueicon|st helens|16}} [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]] (H)\n|bgcolor=DDFFDD| 18-10\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:white;\"| <small>'''Key:''' (H) = Home venue; (A) = Away venue; (N) = [[Home advantage#Neutral venues|Neutral venue]].</small>\n|}\n\n===Wigan Warriors===\n{{See|2016 Wigan Warriors season}}\nWigan have been quieter than usual this season, however in the back end of the season Wigan have fought back to finish second by beating [[Hull F.C.]] and [[Warrington Wolves]] away. However, they have lost their last 2 grand finals, and beat the wolves in 2013. \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;margin-left:1em;float:right\"\n<!-- |+ '''Leeds''' -->\n!width=\"25\" | Round\n!width=\"150\" | Opposition\n!width=\"60\" | Score\n|-\n!scope=row style=\"text-align:center\"| Semi-Final\n| {{leagueicon|hull|16}} [[Hull F.C.]] (H)\n|bgcolor=DDFFDD| 28-18\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background-color:white;\"| <small>'''Key:''' (H) = Home venue; (A) = Away venue; (N) = [[Home advantage#Neutral venues|Neutral venue]].</small>\n|}\n\n==Match day==\n===Pre-game===\nThe match was a rematch of the [[2013 Super League Grand Final]], where Wigan won the trophy after trailing at half-time. This is Wigan's fourth consecutive Grand Final appearance. Warrington have been in the Grand Final twice before and have never won the Super League trophy, with their last league trophy win coming 61 years ago in the [[1954\u201355 Northern Rugby Football League season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/37545067|title=Grand Final: Warrington and Wigan set for Super League's 2016 final|date=7 October 2016|work=BBC SPORT RUGBY LEAGUE|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nWigan were underdogs coming into this match as a host of their regular players were missing through injury. Players such as [[Sam Tomkins|Sam]] and [[Joel Tomkins]], [[Michael McIlorum]], [[Dominic Manfredi]], and [[Lee Mossop]]. Skipper [[Sean O'Loughlin]] was also amongst this list but was rushed into the team for the Grand Final and was placed on the bench after two 'successful' training sessions. Warrington's [[Chris Sandow]] was also a late inclusion for the Grand Final after he recovered enough to play, however he also started the game on the reserves bench.\n\nThis was the last rugby league match for Wigan's [[Josh Charnley]] before heading off to play rugby union. Teammate, [[Lewis Tierney]], son of [[1998 Super League Grand Final]] winner and dual-international, [[Jason Robinson (rugby player)|Jason Robinson]], created history by becoming the first son to play in a Grand Final after his father did.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/rugby-league/550000/Lewis-Tierney-Grand-Final-Saturday-Rugby-League-Wigan-Warriors|title=Lewis Tierney will write his name in the Grand Final history books on Saturday|date=1 October 2016|work=DAILY STAR|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> Notably, Oliver Gildart's father [[Ian Gildart]] had also won various silverware with Wigan, but this was prior to the Super League era.\n\n==Match details==\n{{rugbyleaguebox\n|bg = C1D8FF\n|date = 8 October 2016<br />18:00 [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n|team1 = [[Warrington Wolves]] {{leagueicon|Warrington|16}}\n|score = 6 \u2013 12 \n|report = ([https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/37550948 Report])\n|team2 = {{leagueicon|Wigan|16}} [[Wigan Warriors]]\n|points1 = '''Tries:''' [[Declan Patton|Patton]] {{try|21}}<br>'''Goals:''' [[Declan Patton|Patton]] (1/1) 22'\n|points2 = '''Tries:''' [[Oliver Gildart|Gildart]] {{try|55}}<br>[[Josh Charnley|Charnley]] {{try|63}}<br>'''Goals:''' [[Matty Smith|Smith]] (2/4) 8', 74'\n|stadium = [[Old Trafford]], [[Manchester]] \n|attendance = 70,202\n|referee = Robert Hicks\n|manofmatch = [[Liam Farrell]]\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:138px; background:blue; color:yellow; border:2px solid yellow;\"|'''Warrington Wolves'''\n![[Rugby league positions|Position]]\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:138px; background:red; color:white; border:2px solid white;\"|'''Wigan Warriors'''\n|-\n!6\n| style=\"tex